Incredible!
This is my favorite book of the Harry Potter series, just ahead of the Goblet of Fire.  It caught my interest from the very beginning, in the middle of the summer when Harry is at the Dursley's, which most of the other books did not do.  After the first chapter, it was very hard to put down!  I even ignored the phone ringing several times while I was reading.  <br /><br />Many questions of why and how that I had from previous books were answered in this one.  The story falls together almost perfectly in my opinion, with the exception of a few questions I had concerning the prophecy and it's importance. The only downside to the book was the sad ending during which, as the reviewer above mentioned, I almost cried.  That heartbreaking incident creates a different feeling than was had through the books when Harry was younger.  The mood is darker, and as he gets older, Harry becomes more independent, slowly seperating from Ron, Hermione, Dumbledore (especially in the end), and Hagrid for fear of Voldemort using them to manipulate Harry.  <br /><br />I highly recommend this book to everyone who has read the first 5 books of the series
      
