A bundle of fun/savings
First off, the Xbox 360 has proven to be one of the finest console gaming experiences ever. The excellent roster of games, both upcoming and currently available, along with Microsoft's well-regulated and affordable online service, present a great base experience. In terms of the console's performance, the new Jasper chipset has cut down drastically on the console's propensity to overheat, and results in a quieter, more stable system with a smaller power brick.<br /><br />Xbox Live is a good enough service that I found myself unable to resist purchasing online DLC (downloadable content) for my favorite games. A larger hard drive is essential if you are into augmenting your games with post-release content (although it should be noted that, after you purchase the content, you can always re-download it if you need to delete it to free up space). This console offers a great opportunity for lots of storage, a new, dependable console chipset (my console, purchased a week ago, was manufactured in 2/2010), and two great games to boot.<br /><br />Halo 3: ODST has a fun, if short, campaign along with a hugely addicting single-player or co-op gametype called Firefight. It is well worth picking up if you have any liking for Halo at all.<br /><br />Forza 3 is a very high-quality hybrid racer, part sim, part arcade racer (I found it to lean more towards the simulation, but the game options are very flexible), with lots of cars, tracks and upgrade content. If you like racers, it has a lot to offer.<br /><br />When taken together, this console is a killer deal, essentially throwing in two of the most popular games of 2009 for free. You can't lose, especially if you need to replace an older, less reliable iteration of Microsoft's sometimes-problem-fraught console. If you're new to the Xbox 360, this is a fine way to get into the game, or more specifically, two of the best and most fun games available.
      
