Awesome Gaming Machine BUT The AV Cable Didn't Work For My HDTV!!!!!!!!!!!!
First of all I would like to thank Microsoft for coming up with such a great gaming machine at an excellent price! I just got my Xbox 360 Elite yesterday and I've been playing it all day today. However, I felt the need to comment on one major problem I had when I received my Xbox yesterday. After opening up the box and setting up the gaming machine on my television, I was initially unable to get the system to work. All that came up was a blank blue screen that said "AV 1". After a couple of stressful hours, I decided to call up the Xbox customer support phone number to see if they could come up with a solution. I spoke to the girl on the phone for about 20 minutes and she came to the conclusion that I had a bad AV cable. After taking down my information and registering my Xbox, she told me that I would receive a new AV cable in the mail in about 5-10 days. While I am a patient person in many cases, I was not a very patient person in this situation (come on man it's an Xbox 360 Elite!). I decided to go ahead and buy another cable at a local game shop rather than wait up to 10 days for another one. Instead of buying another standard AV cable, I decided to get the HD AV component cable since my big screen tv has a maximum resolution of 1080i which is a little outdated compared to the newer televisions. It also does not have an HDMI port. After installing the new cable I was very happy to find that it worked! At first I thought the Xbox customer support rep was right about the other cable being faulty. However, I wanted to compare the HD graphics to the standard ones which is why I tried hooking up just the three standard hookups on the HD cable (red, yellow and white). Surprisingly, the blank blue screen came up again which made me come to the conclusion that the problem wasn't the cable the entire time! <br /><br />The reason why I wanted to address this problem is because I don't know whether my problem is very unique or quite common. If it is a common problem, I'm sure many people have drawn the conclusion that their Xbox 360 was broken. If I hadn't purchased the new HD AV component cable, I probably would have done the same and would have sent the Xbox to Microsoft to get fixed. Hope this helps guys and just to let you know I highly recommend this Xbox system. If I'm correct this system has the latest chips which has solved any past problems with the Xbox. Thumbs up Microsoft!<br /><br />P.S. If you had the same problem as me please comment on this review.
      
