he included composite cable and for now I am using an ethernet cable into my wireless router for the xbox live. Even though I have wireless here, the $80 wireless add on is not a necessity right now. One small gripe is the fact Microsoft can't include an HDMI cable or built in wireless but in the end it's all about money. So I included an HDMI cable with the same Amazon order for an extra $8, so not a huge deal. Comparing both hookups on my newer Samsung LCD HDTV it was a huge difference between the composite and HDMI. For less than $10, if you have HDMI, there's no reason not to hook it up that way. The included games are fantastic (they are not full versions of the games but that is stated up front)and the xbox live is sensational. With plenty of downloads and free demos to check out, it keeps one busy for a long time. The graphics are awesome and very realistic. With the xbox live update, I was playing some of my older games like Nascar 2003 that I really love and Star Wars Battlefront 2 and spongebob with my son. These older games worked perfect and was another reason I wanted to stick with Microsoft. These older games I have become addicted to are hard to let go of.  My Netflix account was up and ready in the blink of an eye and looked great with no loss of streaming. This machine runs pretty quiet, even compared to the old system and has not been getting really hot.  I haven't had it running non stop like the old one yet, but so far so good on the overheating issue. Still too early though. While I can't compare it to a Sony platform, I can say if you are like me and have waited to buy this machine, do it now and go ahead and take the leap. From what I have encountered so far, it is an outstanding machine and a ton of fun at a decent price.
      
