Good system, somewhat tacky graphics
Let me start off this review by saying that I own all three current-gen systems (although this review will not be comparing them). Prior to purchasing this 360, I owned a falcon Elite (which I purchased for the HDMI and 120GB HDD), and prior to that, I owned a xenon Premium (which I sold due to its lack of an HDMI port). All of the MW2 360s are the new jasper chipset, which for the consumer essentially means that the 360 is quieter, runs cooler, and uses less energy (150w max vs 175w for falcon, and 203w for xenon/zepyher).<br /><br />So how is the MW2 360? Well it's a better 360 than older ones, comes with more storage, and if you like what the 360 offers, then you will like this console more than the other 360 variants. If you don't like the 360, then the 360 page on Amazon is probably not the place for you. So to not drag on, here are some pros and cons of this specific bundle as compared to other 360 bundles:<br /><br />Pros:<br />+250GB Hard Drive<br />+Extra Controller<br />+Free Modern Warfare 2 Game<br />+Smaller Power Supply (about 2/3-3/4 size of original PSU)<br />+Black Bezel (personal preference, I prefer black over chrome)<br />+Jasper chipset<br /><br />Cons:<br />-Looks like someone spilled gray paint on console. (High speed, low drag? Joint Task Force? Seriously?)<br />-Doesn't come with HDMI cable or HDAV cable like previous Elite consoles. Has only a composite cable, which is pathetic; oddly no current-gen systems come with anything better than a composite cable.<br />-Audio adapter (with HDMI cable) is a $50 separate purchase. HDMI cables are cheap on Monoprice (and video quality is equal for all digital cables), but the audio adapter if you need to output the audio not via HDMI is a proprietary Microsoft cable.<br /><br />Despite these cons, this bundle is still worth getting (and is the best value in comparison to other 360 bundles) if you're looking to buy an Xbox 360 console.
      
