Upgrade Complete
I FINALLY upgraded to a PS3 this Christmas and I am incredibly happy I did.  While I have always and WILL always love my PS2 I had to see what the PS3 was all about.<br /><br />The new system offers so many applications and possibilities that the PS2 never could.  The online system is fun, though I don't use it as often as many do.  I enjoy being able to surf the net and have direct play from Netflix.  I also love the PlayStation store for upgrades for certain games.<br /><br />The size of the console seemed normal to me, though many still complain that it's large.  The PS2 wasn't the smallest console and this model is no different.  The Slim model is obviously smaller and uses far less energy than the larger PS3.  It doesn't make a sound while running.  There's no sound of fans, lasers moving, etc.<br /><br />I would have to say my favorite addition is the wireless controller.  I love that you can turn the console on and off through the controller and that some games (such as "Lair") use the Sixaxxis to it's fullest capacity.  My only complaint would be how you charge them.  If you don't spend the money on a charging pad you have to use a short USB cable that comes with the console.  While you can still play a game while charging you have to sit close enough so you don't pull it off your TV.<br /><br />The graphics on the PS3 are wonderful.  Every game I've played (Assassin's Creed 1 & 2, Eternal Sonata, Lair, Little Big Planet, etc.) are beautifully created with graphics that often suggest they could step out of your screen they look so real.  The sound if also amazing.<br /><br />The only other complaint I would have about the PS3 Slim is it's matte finish.  I do appreciate that it doesn't collect fingerprints like the larger models shines finish did, but the new finish is textured and therefore holds dust way too well.<br /><br />Overall the PS3 gets 5/5 stars.  I would rate it higher if I could.  I have been completely happy with the new console and often wonder what the heck took me so long when it came to buying it...oh...that's right...it used to cost $600.
      
