The reason to buy a PS3
I will have to start out by saying I am a MGS fan from NES days. That simple statement is to warn people that while I try to be as honest as possible I do have some bias towards the game and series. <br /><br />If you don't own a PS3 yet MGS4 is the reason to buy one. This is the fitting end of an era for Solid Snake and the game is a master piece of art, story and gameplay. That said this is Hideo Kojima's story and he is going to make damn sure you see it. While I am not sure of the percentage I would guess at least a third of the game is made up of cut scenes. You will watch through entire stages of cuts scenes, only to save and watch another one before getting to a playable stage. For the less than total MGS fan this can be quite annoying. Luckily you are able to skip the scenes if you want, though you will lose all understanding of the story in the process. And like all previous MGS titles on the PS systems this is a complex and convoluted story. But for the fan it will answer so many of the questions that have up to this point been unresolved in the series. <br /><br />The gameplay is typical MGS but even more refined and precise than before. While I thought it would be hard to top the control available in MGS3 this game has done it. Snake moves with amazing precision, but with a real world weight to him. Snake is an old soldier and it shows. But while any other person his age would be home watching TV, Snake is out to save the world one last time. The years of hard live come across clearly in the gameplay while not being an unnecessary hindrance. The fact that Hideo Kojima was able to pull this off is amazing. The amount of Easter Eggs and homages to the series and his past game means several play through are in order for the fan. The amount of gear and weapons also means most players will play through several times just to make sure they have experience all the action. <br /><br />You can not go wrong with this game, be it for the hardcore MGS fan, or the fan of action games in general. This is the fitting end of Hideo Kojima run on this amazing series and it ends with every bit as much emotional investment as Lord of the Rings or Star Wars. There may be Metal Gear games in the future, I hope there are, but this is the fitting end of Snakes tale.
      
