i'm not even a gamer.
I'm not even a gamer like that. I'm one of those ppl who bought my PS3 for the blu-ray to give you an idea, & I bought a few games initially (FIFA 10, Modern Warfare 2) which held my attention, but nothing like this. <br /><br />With the tutorials, it shouldn't be hard for someone who hasn't gamed in years to get a pretty decent grasp on how to play. <br /><br />There have been some frustrations w/some of the challenges (lasso the horse, anyone??) but nothing that took me out the game.
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Single player is amazing.
I'll try to keep this short and sweet.  Let's start by addressing the technical issues:  yes, there is pop-in, occasional slow-down, and the random odd glitch, but has there ever been a Rockstar game for which this wasn't the case?  And, more importantly, these things don't detract from the experience at all, at least not for me.<br /><br />The world is much better realized than in GTA IV, with more possible interaction with NPCs, and the random encounters are a great deal of fun.  Also, R* San Diego has 'fixed' some of the features of GTA that were always irksome, such as health (which now regenerates if you avoid further injury), failing missions (which now offers you a 'Restart from checkpoint' option that usually only puts you back a minute or so in gameplay), and the ability to replay any mission you've completed at any time through the pause menu (thank you!).  The only step backward from the GTA franchise is that your character, John Marston, dies pretty much instantly in water.  Didn't these guys ever see Butch and Sundance?  Cowboys should be able to swim.<br /><br />I haven't touched the (reportedly buggy) multiplayer yet, but with as much fun as I'm having just riding around rescuing people from bandits and trying to avoid becoming a cougar's lunch, I haven't missed it at all.<br /><br />Whether or not you'll connect with it probably comes down to your feelings about westerns and/or open world games, but I can say without hesitation that I have more fun with RDR than I did with either GTA IV or Fallout 3, both of which I thought were excellent open world experiences.
      
