<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Amazing Multi-Player Experience!
Many users have already commented on the New Super Mario Bros. game itself, but what I wanted to know before I purchased this game was how the multi-player experience worked out.  Obviously, four players can journey through each level at one time, but I have to say that the actual experience proved far more fun than I had anticipated.  <br /><br />What I find so ingenious about the multi-player experience is how thoroughly each player can affect one another while going through a level.  While you can't directly kill one another, you can block and push each other, shoot each other with shells, bounce off of each other's heads to go higher, steal each other's mushrooms and other bonuses, and even kill one another by moving so far ahead on the screen that another player gets scrolled off of it.  This essentially allows you to experience three different and incredibly fun multi-player experiences without adjusting any settings to the game:<br /><br />-Brawl style: Go through the levels with the primary goal of trying to eliminate each other.  This is tremendously fun as well as challenging.  <br /><br />-Every man for him/herself: A bit chaotic and often incredibly funny.  It's impossible not to get in each other's way when everyone is working for his/herself, and the little accidents that can happen along the way are often downright hysterical.<br /><br />-Cooperative style: My friends and I have had too much fun trying it the other ways, but it's clear that the game takes on a whole new shape is a team coordinates its efforts, using each other to jump higher, saving bonuses for each other, and carefully moving through the screen at the same pace.  I look forward to trying this once the fun of slaughtering one another begins to wane (which may never happen).<br /><br />All in all, New Super Mario Bros. introduces a very new and incredibly worthwhile open-ended multi-player experience.  I never imagined a four player side-scroller could work, but Nintendo has proven me wrong and then some.  Goodbye Mario Kart and Smash Bros.  My friends and I will be playing New Super Mario Bros. together for years to come.<br /><br />** Side note: When playing in four player mode, we've noticed some frusterating lag time that occurs several times per level.  If too much happens at once, the game freezes for a fraction of a second, which inevitably messes all of us up.  I have no idea whether this is caused by our specific Wii, our copy of the game, or if this is a defect in the game design, itself.  You get used to the lags after a while, but they seem absurdly unnecessary in this age of console gaming.
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Two Words: Multiplayer Mayhem
I've been a long time gamer, and remember the good old days even back with Super Mario Bros. For me, this game was going to be a must-have.<br /><br />I've really enjoyed this game. For those who have played Super Mario Bros. 3 and Super Mario World, the feel of the game is identical, and it adds so much more to the table. It also mixes in elements from other Mario games.<br /><br />First of all, the environments are well done. The design of the levels are innovative and bring some freshness to the game. From trying to stay on moving, rotating blocks, to riding atop massive manta rays, to narrowly avoiding giant spiked pillars that smash into walls, to riding a skeleton dragon roller coaster, the levels designs showcase amazing creativity.<br /><br />The basics of the control scheme will be familiar to those who've played Super Mario before. The controller is held sideways, the 2 Button is jump, the 1 Button is dash, which you also use to hold things or to throw fire/ice balls. In addition, you can also spin the Wii Remote to do a spin jump. If you want to pick up something heavy, you just hold the 1 Button and spin the Wii Remote. The first few times when you can spin the Wii Remote to do something, a nice little reminder will appear above your character.<br /><br />In this game, they've also added in some new and interesting power ups. In addition to a number of familiar power ups, such as the fire flower and mini mushroom, there's the ice flower, the propeller suit, and the penguin suit. I did like these new power ups, but I personally would like to have seen some more.<br /><br />The difficulty of the game starts off pretty low, but the game does get harder as you go along. Some of the later levels definitely require an added measure of patience. Also, some of the later boss battles are just cheap (For example, three moving platforms with the boss always occupying one, and a pit below - I fell off and died a few times even after beating the boss!).<br /><br />Where this game really shines is in its multiplayer. As you know (and if you don't, you should), this game sports multiplayer in a new and longly anticipated way for a Mario game. You're able to play through levels with four players co-operatively. There's a couple of modes you can also play to battle each other with, but I'll just focus on the co-op. Trust me when I tell you that this is one of those games where every time you play it with friends, you bust up laughing at something someone does. The multiplayer is by far the best feature of the game. Without it, it's "just" another Mario game (though a pretty good one, all the same).<br /><br />With the multiplayer, all mayhem breaks loose. Playing this game, I've been known to chuck people off the edge, use others to attack enemies, throw someone into an enemy if they steal all the power ups, bounce on someone's head to garner enough height to make it to a ledge, pick up someone to carry them through a section, and so on. It's amazing fun, especially when you have more people.<br /><br />In multiplayer, things act a little differently. First of all, in most cases, when you hit a ? block, that contains a power up, there will be enough power ups for everyone. Another thing is if someone goes down a pipe or through a door, after a few moments, even if no one else has gone there, it will go to that part of the level. Also, if someone dies, they immediately loose a life, and after a few seconds will appear back on screen in a bubble that needs to be popped (If they lose their last life, then they won't come back until you return to the level select screen. once there, they'll start back up with five lives). In addition, if you come up to a harder section, they can hit A to turn into a bubble retaining their power up until someone pops them out again. Be warned on that, though, if everyone either dies or is in a bubble, you will get booted out of the level.<br /><br />It's also entertaining to play levels meant for one person with up to four people. For example, playing alone, let's say there's a platform that you have a little room to move on. Now, imagine that same platform with four people on it. People are bouncing off of each other, others have picked up someone and -oops, one of them let go of the 1 Button and just killed that person, but they'll be coming back in a bubble soon. Who ever thought that it could get so crowded!<br /><br />All around, New Super Mario Bros. Wii is a great game with classic gameplay, innovative levels, and most notably multiplayer madness. I highly recommend it to anyone looking for a great game on the Wii.
      
