Nice upgrade to Wii Fit
Wii Fit is excellent.  I've been using it for almost a year now.  Wii Fit Plus is a nice upgrade with 3 new advanced yoga exercises, 3 new advanced strength exercises plus 15 new balance games. Add to that some user improvements and it's an easy 5 star program.<br /><br />Of course using Wii Fit is not equal to jogging 5 miles or spending an hour with weights but for those that don't consider themselves intermediate or advanced athletes the exercises are strenuous enough to improve balance, strength and endurance if used 3 or more times a week.<br /><br />For those that that don't like to exercise the games are worth the price.
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Worth the Price
I must admit I had gotten a little bored with the original Wii Fit, so when I saw the Wii Fit Plus in the store I picked it up. Overall this game is very fun and definitely worth the price. As many reviewers have said the addition of the new games is spot on. They keep me coming back every morning (so far). <br /><br />I also have to speak to the problem that I see a few others are having with the new routines. The game allows for you to choose to work on certain areas (health, youth, etc.) and the game will set up a routine that is as long or short as you want. You also have the choice to combine all areas. Nintendo has also given players the option to set up their own routines. Although the routines the game chooses include yoga, strength, aerobics, and the new games, the routines that the player sets up can only include yoga and strength. At first I was a little disappointed by this. But I think, for myself, this is probably for the best. By using the routines the game provides I am getting a nice mix of yoga, strength, and the fun mini-games. If I was dictating my routines I can guarantee that I would cut corners. Besides, it makes it less boring when I don't know what exercise is coming next. I don't know if this is why the makers chose to do it this way or if it is just an oversight in the game but, so far, it works for me. I think Nintendo did an excellent job with the routines and it got me doing some of the strength exercises that I had never done before (oops)!<br /><br />Overall this game is worth the low price tag and it will keep me using the Wii Fit for a while longer.
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Loving it!
Sweeeeeeet! I am loving the Wii Fit Plus! Just got it in the mail yesterday from Amazon and I'm impressed with the improvements Nintendo made.<br /><br />Here are some of my favorite features:<br />1. My biggest complaint about the original was that I had to use my remote between every exercise and scroll through the menus to what I wanted, making a 30-minute workout into more like 45 or 60 minutes. You can now choose from suggested workouts based on your goals (like shedding some extra calories, slimming your figure or relaxation), or you can customize your own using yoga and strength training. You still need the remote when you use the suggested workouts, but if you make up your own, there is no button pushing so you can put the remote down for the whole time. Plus, it saves the workout you designed so you can use it again and again, or you can easily swap out an exercise or two. **The only thing I'm not crazy about is that the suggested workouts incorporate the balance games and aerobics, but you can't include them in your own customized workout. Still a big improvement, especially since doing the yoga feels more like a flow now instead of pose, stop, pose, stop, etc.<br /><br />2. I love that there's a multiplayer mode so it's easy to play with other people -- but don't get your hopes up too high: You only get to pick from nine games (soccer heading, ski slolam, ski jump, balance bubble, hula hoop, obstacle course, Bird's-Eye Bull's-Eye, driving range and snowball fight).<br /><br />3. I'm really enjoying most of the 15 new games on the Plus, such as rhythm kung fu, the obstacle course, snowball fight, rhythm parade, Segway circuit and a more challenging table tilt. You also get three new strength exercises and three new yoga poses.<br /><br />4. The Plus tracks the approximate number of calories you burn. It also lets you set a goal of how much you'd like to burn in a session as well as a chart to help you see how that might compare to the calories in common foods.<br /><br />5. In the Favorites section, it not only lists the activities you do the most, it also lists what you've done more recently and what you have done the least so you can mix it up more if you want to or stick with the ones you like.<br /><br />6. The Body Test has additional tests that challenge both your balance and your mind. Glad to have a few more things it might throw at me after doing the same tests for the past two months now.<br /> <br />7. Under the Chart menu, it not only tracks your BMI, Weight, Wii Fit Age and Fit Credits (where you can record outside exercise), Nintendo has added a place to record your waist measurement and your steps. <br /><br />The new activities and customizable workouts are a nice boost to my motivation to work out, which I admit was starting to wain. I am also happy with the price of the game; I believe the new features are well worth the $20.
      
