Wildly Amazing
In many ways, Mario really hasn't changed much from the time of scurrying through level 1-1 in 1985.  You still run as fast as you can to the end of the stage, stomp on enemies, hit powerup blocks and the like.  But of course why change what isn't broken.  Like the original SMG, SMG2 is a spiritual successor to Super Mario 64.  Once again, Nintendo uses their flagship mascot to put out a genre defining game.<br /><br />It could be argued to give SMG2 a lower score than the original merely because it isn't the giant leap forward the original was. I find this misguided.  Mario has always been about pinpoint control and perfect level design, two things shown here in spades.  There is not a single boring level and there is always something new to do.  Be it reaching new comet coins, solving puzzles or any of the other platforming activities. <br /><br />The game is difficult.  Not to breeze through and finish, but to find every star and comet coin.  This allows a gamer to feel accomplished after breezing through a selection of levels while finding enough to do for the hardcore gamer.  Its the perfect mix.<br /><br />No, it isn't HD graphics, but the art design is beautiful.  Simply put, some gamers have abandoned Nintendo because they feel they have outgrown Mario and the cartoonish ways.  However, they are missing out because Mario is still consistantly the best games available.  Amazing game.
      
