A gamer's portable
First of all expect to spend much more than $169 before you can enjoy the PSP. Once you add a memory card, a couple of games, a case and a skin or screen protector, you would've spent over $200.00 before you even take the system home. However, the PSP experience is still incredible almost 5 years after it came out. Far more powerful and technologically superior to the DS and capable of providing deep, detailed gameplay compared to the iPhone's short attention span offerings, the PSP is a true gamer's console with the following great features:<br /><br />-Great library of games covering RPGs, action, sports, etc etc. They retail for about $30 to $40 but eBay always has tons of used or NOS games for less than $20 every day. <br />-Capable of playing Nintendo, Super Nintendo, N64, PS1, Sega Master, Sega Genesis and other games from older systems via freely available emulators<br />-Capable of wirelessly controlling a PS3 and using media on the bigger machine.<br />-Capable of browsing the internet and download games, demos, themes and other media via WiFi. The demos help in game buying decisions while the themes allow the user to personalize their PSP<br /><br />All in all the PSP may be old but nothing in the market can touch its gaming horsepower. If you like your on the go games to be just as detailed and complex as your home console games then you owe yourself a PSP.
      
