<!-- BOUNDARY -->
What is Everyone Expecting?
A few things first... I don't own a PSP 3000, and I have no UMD discs to transfer. I'm a lifelong Sony customer, and I've been burned by them many times before--the stack of MiniDiscs to my left as I write this is a nice reminder. <br /><br />I keep coming back because their products appeal to me--they're often innovative, they look/feel great, and their audio quality is in my opinion, always the benchmark. Yes, Sony's products are expensive, but so is everything Apple releases. <br /><br />I'm not a hardcore gamer, but I enjoy playing for a few hours in an airport or on a flight while traveling for business. I've been using an iPod Touch in this capacity, and while it's a magnificent device, I'm just not a touch-screen gamer. <br /><br />I also wanted something with a bit bigger screen, better battery life, and better sound. Essentially, I was looking for a device between the Touch and an Archos. The PSP Go turned out to be the perfect size with the features I wanted. <br /><br />A few observations:<br /><br />PROS: The screen is knockout gorgeous, and better than the iPod Touch. Video playback is beautiful. And it plays Divx!<br /><br />Audio quality is Sony-level outstanding.<br /><br />Feels great in my hands, sleek, sexy design, slide out controls, and a nice compact size (slightly bigger than a Touch.) That was the main reason I never bought a PSP 3000--too big. <br /><br />The ability to listen to music, watch video, play "real" games without leaving fingerprints all over the screen, check the Web via Wi-Fi, listen to/watch podcasts, and store it in my bag without any annoying peripherals is a joy.<br /><br />External slot for Memory Stick Micro means it's not "stuck" with an out-of-the-box storage capacity.  <br /><br />CONS: It wouldn't be Sony without a suspicious pricetag attached, for both hardware and software. However, Archos is still the price-gouge leader on portable devices, and Apple isn't far behind, so Sony isn't alone in that club.<br /><br />Podcast subscriptions from the Sony Media Go software are limited. However, if you go to iTunes, you can right click on any podcast, select "Copy Podcast URL" and paste it into the Media Go "Subscribe to URL" option. It's worked for every podcast I selected.<br /><br />OVERALL: An outstanding, ultra-portable multimedia device that is about much more than games. However, Sony needs to find it in their DNA to lower the prices. They did with the PS3--so it's not impossible, but the window is closing.
      
