(even on high settings) but you could easily see the dark areas of a picture on the PSP's screen. The PSP's screen is big as a 3x5 flash card, which is great, I think.<br /><br />As a Web Broswer Viewer, it's neat but takes time to get use to. Since there's no keyboard, it's hard using the menu keyboard on the PSP. Heavy imaged/video sites will not work on the PSP, but a lot of other sites work fine on it.<br /><br />As a Game Player, the graphics like everyone says...are compared to PS2 graphics. Although, I can't really compare much on gaming on the system yet, since I haven't purchase a game for it yet. Although the PSP's game lineup is promising...plus if you have a PS3, you could purchase and download PS1 games off the PS Store and play the PS1 games on your PS1! PS1 games are around 200-500MBs big, so this is where having a 4GB Memory Stick could get useful.<br /><br />In conclusion, if you like to game, watch videos, play music (off the memory card or wireless stream!), using a web browser, viewing pictures sometimes, or have a PS3...I would recommend getting the PSP. <br /><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0009VXAM0">Sony PlayStation 3 (60GB)</a><br /><br />***It would be highly recommended that you know some computer lingo (like using wireless stuff, computer programs, formats, etc) and such with the PSP in the long run.***<br /><br />As well, I would highly recommend getting a screen protector too, because the screen WILL get scratch after use. <a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0007XOHYK">Sony PSP Screen Guard Twin Pack</a><br /><br />Other items I would recommend would be a pouch case, PSP headphone+remote (mainly for music playback), GO for a 4GB Memory Stick PRO Duo (if you plan to store movies on it),  and a USB cable if you don't have one already.<br /><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0009KVDNY">Sony PSP Accessory Carrying Case And Cloth</a><br /><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0007V46IY">Sony PSP Headphones with Remote Control</a><br />4GB Memory Stick Pro Duo<br /><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0009DPQYI">Sony PSP USB Cable</a><br /><br />**A parent recommendation, if you are buying this for your son/daughter...for one, make sure they'll plan to use it (or else, it will be a costly mistake), they will be careful with it (because a drop on the sidewalk will break the PSP in some cases). The PSP, in my opinion, is geared towards teens from 13 and up.
      
