Very comfortable; decent sound quality; trade up to save money
I just traded in my Quiet Comfort 2's for these QC 15's.  My comparison between the two follows.  <br /><br />Durability.  The reason I traded my old "2"s in was that the side "arm" broke, despite my very gentle use of them.  I took them into the Bose store, and they acknowledged that the breaking side arms was a common problem.  They also assured me that the QC15's have been upgraded and fortified not once but twice since the particular version of the QC2's that I previously owned.  They say this one is much more durable; I suppose time will tell.<br /><br />Price.  You should know that if you are upgrading from QC2, as I am, you can trade them in at the Bose store and get one hundred fifty dollars off your purchase of the QC15's.  Technically, they have to be defective, but my salesman told me that just me stating that they were defective would be good enough for them.<br /><br />Sound.  The noise cancelling seems a bit better than the QC2's to my ear.  I played a couple songs with heavy bass and it came through quite distorted on the QC15's.  If you care about rich bass, you will probably be disappointed.<br /><br />Case.  It's a bit sexier than the old QC2 case.
      
