Fantastic
I own the original model of the Bose noise canceling earphones, as well as a pair of small folding Senheiser noise canceling phones.  This new Bose model is clearly a step up from the original Bose, not to mention not having the separate battery and electronics case that was part of the original.  The level of sound isolation seems phenomenal, though I have yet to wear them on a plane flight.  If quiet is all you want, the cord to a sound source can be removed entirely.  They do not fold, but the ear cups do rotate so that the device packs flat.  It comes with a well designed, form fitting travel case (as well as a supply of business cards describing the phones you can give to envious fellow travelers!).  I was pleased to find that there is room inside the case for an iPod as well as the phones.  <br /><br />I cannot truly judge the sound quality from an audiophile standpoint; I am a 71 year old man with good hearing for my age, but my high frequency hearing is unquestionably age-impaired.  Given that, however, I find the sound quality to be good.  The phones are on the heavy side, but not excessively so for their size.  This may become a problem after wearing them for long periods, however.  Also, I find that the closed, ear-surrounding ear cups become noticeably warm.<br /><br />One drawback that must be mentioned is that Bose phones cannot be used in a non-cancelling mode, or with a dead battery.  This can be a significant issue if one has not planned ahead and packed an extra battery or two inside the case.  At this point, I cannot say how long a battery will last in use.  <br /><br />Overall, the biggest drawback to these phones is their size.  They and the case take up a significant amount of space in a briefcase or purse.  In return, however, one gets the extreme sound isolation provided and good quality sound if one wants to listen to music or podcasts while using them at home or on the road.
      
