I'm in love....
We moved into a house with lots of tile and wood, and after a year of avoiding cleaning my floors because of the time and effort involved and being embarrassed by the dirt on my feet and socks, I decided it was time to look for a solution. I started researching steam mops, largely because we have also started going green and it seemed the perfect solution. I started with the Shark, and the reviews were awful regarding the sturdiness of the handle. Then I looked at some of the cheaper models available in the big box stores, and again, reviews were not that great. Reviews were best for the Haan and the Monster, so I started focusing there. Coincidentally, my neighbor called to tell me that Big Lots had Sharks on sale and she was getting one for her daughter in law because she loved hers, did I want one? I said "no", but can I give yours a test run? Being a good neighbor, she said yes. I must tell you, I loved that stinking mop. It made my floors so clean and took a fraction of the time. I wavered between going ahead with the Shark (she'd had hers a year with no problems) and the Monster, but I found a good deal here on Amazon and opted to go with the Monster. I am so happy I did! The Monster is SOOOOOOOO much easier to push than the Shark. Also, the pad, hence cleaning surface, is much bigger. I also liked the steam jets for use around the toilet and shower alot. The psychological thrill I get about that super hot steam blasting my 2 boys toilet is significant.... The steam jets are also good for getting stuck items off. The aim takes a little practice, but a couple of blasts have been all I needed for most problem areas. Shark heats up much faster, but doesn't hold as much water or get as hot as the Monster. I wouldn't say that the handle is rock solid on the Monster, but all the reviews I've read on many sites seem to indicate that it's not nearly the problem it is with the Shark. I've only found one that said it actually broke whereas the Shark reviews I read complained consistently about it breaking. The Haan seems to be a good brand too, but I liked the look of the Monster better, so that's the direction I went. Honestly, if I'd never heard of the Monster and had only used the Shark, I would have been totally happy to use it over mopping. However, now that I've used both, I have to say the Monster beats the Shark hands down. I do not plan to use this on carpets as it does not seem to be a good solution. Why would I steam my carpets with no suction? Maybe it's a European thing. However, as a solution for hard surfaces, and in reference to my 2 kids, I yell from the mountaintops.....I LOVE THIS MONSTER!<br />
      
