<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Production!! ...and here's a Vista fix as well
This is the third scanner I have purchased. I have thousands of slides from my travels over the last 40 years and I wanted to digitize them. The other two were single feeds and I didn't have the patience to sit there and wait for it to scan.<br /><br />But this scanner is great. I think the resulting pics are quite good. You can do 16 at a time. People who are complaining about the scans being too blue, etc., are not taking the time to actually learn how to use it.<br /><br />You load the slides. Then do some basic edits for each slide. Then you sit back and let it run. I do it while watching  TV. <br /><br />I've been using the default 300 ppi and for my purposes it is just fine. If it is really a great pic then I up it to 600.<br /><br />Note: for those who had trouble installing in Vista - here's the fix. As usual, the HP tech staff had no clue. <br /><br />The scanner program is still looking for flash.ocx despite the fact that the world has moved on. <br /><br />You probably have flash9.ocx or something like that. So you need to MAKE A COPY AND RENAME IT flash.ocx in the right folder. <br /><br />Directions as follows.<br /><br />Go to Windows>System32>Macromed>Flash and copy flash9.ocx. Might be flash8 or flash who knows, any of them should work. Paste it back into the SAME directory and change the COPIED file to flash.ocx. <br /><br />Do not delete your flash8 or flash9.ocx. Other programs are using it.<br /><br />Restart your computer. Should fix it. <br /><br />Good idea to do this before you try installing the HP scanner software. I installed and uninstalled mine three times before I found this fix on the internet.<br /><br />------Update May 8 - the more I use this scanner the more I like it. I usually scan 2 or 3 batches a day. My backlog is actually diminishing. Doing a great job.<br /><br />------Update August 13, 2009. Have scanned in approx 3,000 plus slides and really appreciate this scanner. I leave all the settings neutral except I do have the dust/scratch remover set to on. Still using 300. Tried higher settings but just takes longer and produces much fatter files. Don't see that much difference at the sizes I am viewing. <br /><br />I bought Adobe Lightroom and I find that to be a very good tool to organize and do simple sizing, cropping, etc. If you have PS/Elements you can easily pop over into that for more chopping. If you aren't really into photography then Google's freebie Picasa is quite good and very easy to use.<br /><br />**********Feb 15, 2010. *****************Owners read this.<br />HP has new scanning software available on their website. Freebie. Well worth the time. Does a much better job of finding and outlining the slides. Almost 100% which is a big improvement. 10000% better at doing pre-editing.  You don't have to click in and out of each slide which was so time consuming. Now they show the pics in a slider and you can click on one, fix it, and go onto the next. Saves a lot of time because you get a nice big pic to look at and you tweak it, or you can decide to not bother with the scan. Some very nice systems work there. Makes this even more desirable. I'm using Windows7 and no install problems like before. Maybe they read this review. ;)<br /><br />Update on new sw: warning. Be careful when using the "remove dust and scratches" function. It can erase eyebrows and other facial features. I quit using it. Still, the new sw is great and really decreases the time it takes to process your slides.<br /><br />
      
