<!-- BOUNDARY -->
Durable & Spacious
My husband and I love to go camping and go on average 20days a year.  This tent requires the use of two people to set up. As always read the instructions first and follow the instructions to a "T". Make sure you do a practice run to get a feel for how the tent is set up. It took about 15-20min for 2 people to set up in moderate weather. This tent is wonderful for the durability and roominess of the tent cabin. Most tent rods are flimsy metal rods connected together with bungee-like elastic cord. The tent rods that go to this tent are sectional metal rods put together that will withstand high gusty winds (35+mph) without compromising the rod/tent structure. This tent is roomy considering that you can easily fit two queen size air mattresses and still have room to put other essential camping gear inside the tent. There are plenty of windows in this tent. One feature I really like about this tent is that it has two doors. Coming from a previous Dome tent owner (and the fact that I am 5'11")the Eureka Cabin tent is a godsend as you can stand up completely in every area of the tent. One word of caution though, when opening and closing windows and doors, zip up the windows and doors carefully or else it will get caught on the tent fabric. As for the tent stakes that come with the tent, trash them. Buy metal tent stakes as they will stay in the ground better. Additionally, the tent floor material is the same the tent side material, so buying a standard tarp underneath the tent is a must if you want to keep your tent floor from getting punctured. Overall, I would recommend this tent to other campers, especially ones with families.<br /><br />
      
