great easy old-fashioned cooking
This is a great product and I am happy with the way it splits up into two separate cooking tools.  I gave my cousin the cover which serves as a shallow skillet and she's been happily using it everyday.  I have not used my deep skillet yet but I plan to cook my next braised stew in it.
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
I love this set!
I've had this set for a month and a half now.  It was the first piece of cast iron cookware I've used (other then my mom's rarely used one growing up) and I have to say that I am totally shocked by how many uses I am finding for this set!  The "lid" is a wonderful 10" skillet that fits a lot of stuff my old 8" didn't without being huge.  The "base" is great for just about anything, including cooking rice which tends to stick to stainless.<br />I've stopped using all of my other cookware and am using this for just about everything!  I've even stopped using the microwave to heat things up.  Instead I just whip one of these out and I've got a great meal without that "reheated" quality that tends to come out of the microwave.<br /><br />I was worried about dealing with the seasoning (or potential lack there of) that came with it, so I spent some time doing my own.  Here's what I did: I covered the inside with a thick coating of oil (I used an olive / coconut oil mix).  Thick enough that it was coated, but not so much that it slid around.  Then I heated them on my stove top until the oil started to smoke a little then I turned it off and left it overnight.  Then in the morning I heated them up again and let them cool off before wiping them out.  The first thing I cooked was hashbrowns, which probably wasn't the best choice.  It stuck a bit, but nowhere near a bad as my stainless cookware, but as soon as it cooled any remains flaked right off.  The next couple times I chose to cook things that needed oil and haven't had any trouble since.  In about a week of use I had a really nice non-stick surface that has gotten better the more I use it.<br /><br />I have this little tip for those of you that use a hanging pot rack: I tend to wash my cookware as soon as I'm done with it (use HOT water for cast iron!) and then hang them up on the rack to dry, but I found that the cast iron, especially the deep "base", would have a little dot of rust on the inside edge where that last drop or two would lay.  So I took a piece of cardboard (I actually used an edge off of the base of a frozen pizza), bent it a little and placed it in the kettle to wick up that last drop or two.  It works great, and no more worrying about rust!<br /><br />I'd really recommend this set if you are new to cast iron.  You can cook just about everything in these two pieces!
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
The Best Baked Potatoes You Have Ever Eaten
If you have never cooked baked potatoes in a cast iron dutch oven or a cast iron skillet with a cast iron cover, you don't know what you are missing.  A little butter and salt, stick them in the oven for the greatest tasting potatoes you have ever eaten.  It also works equally as well with sweet potatoes.  This is a wonderful cooker---everyone should have one!!!! Purchased from AMAZON!<br /><br />
      
