Perfect all around pot/skillet
I've been using this combo cooker for about 2 months.  It lives on top of the stove since I use it nearly daily.  I've used the bottom for soups and casseroles. The top is great for eggs or browning potatoes for Sunday morning breakfast.  I've also used to top to make nachos and then re-heat the leftovers.<br />I own some of the high end non-stick cookware and it is getting no use since I bought this piece.  In fact I was disappointed when I realised that I had to use one of the high end pots to boil pasta the other night, I was wishing I had a Lodge Cast Iron piece that I could use.<br />The consistent even heat is a huge plus, especially when working on sauces.<br />The only drawback is the actual weight of the pan.  Cast iron is heavy which makes it such a great cooking medium.  So now I consider cooking a meal another opportunity to getting so weight lifting into my day!<br />I will be purchasing more Lodge Cast Iron cookware, and giving away my high end cookware to family.
      
<!-- BOUNDARY -->
GREAT cookware that you can easily make non-stick
This is a GREAT and very useful cookware set. I also have a set of Le Creuset enameled cast iron cookware, which cost tons of money, but I love Lodge since it's so cheap but it's such as great quality. Ideally you use this for sautee or deep fry, since the iron cast allows high heat and good distribution of heat. Food tastes better compared to non stick pans, and it's definitely non toxic.<br /><br />It says pre-seasoned but you might need to re-season it to make it raelly non stick. Put a generous layer of vegetable shortening and stick it in the oven for a couple of hours, then leave it overnight to cool off, then rinse with hot water to clean. Don't rub too hard when cleaning so the coating won't wear off. Re-season as needed, usually after a few months of use. Food will slide easily and cleaning is also easy when you rinse with very hot water.
      
